Root cause:
  Gmail returns 404 "Requested entity was not found" for message IDs that are
  already deleted or stale entries from the progress file. The rescue audit
  code intended to skip those. However, gmail_sorter.execute_with_retries()
  classified the error text as retryable because the Gmail request URL included
  the string "metadataHeaders=X-Campaign", which contains "campaign"; the old
  retry check used a broad substring match for "rate". This caused each stale
  404 to go through exponential backoff before the rescue audit could skip it.
  With retries=8 and retry_sleep=8, a single stale 404 could waste a very long
  time, making the log look empty/stalled.

Fix applied:
  Modified src/gmail_sorter.py so execute_with_retries() uses the explicit
  HTTP status when present:
    - retries 429 and 5xx
    - retries 403 only for quota/rate-limit text
    - preserves fallback text matching when no status is available
    - does not retry 404

Regression test added:
  tests/test_trash_rescue_audit.py now includes test_gmail_404_is_not_retried,
  asserting a 404 request is executed once even when retries=8.

